{
  "doc_id": "8958",
  "text": "Exposure to environmental estrogens during critical developmental windows has welldocumented adverse consequences on males and females of many species, including rodents and humans [National Institutes of Health (NIH) 1999; [CITATION_1] . One group of environmental endocrine disruptors that is currently receiving significant attention is the naturally occurring phyto estrogens (for review, see [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] ). These compounds are readily available in the diet, particularly in soy products [CITATION_4] Lapcik et al. 1998; [CITATION_5] . The major class of phyto estrogens found in soy is isoflavones; the phyto estrogen in that class that has received the most attention is genistein (GEN). GEN is primarily present in its glycosylated forms, with genistin (GIN), the 4′-β-d-glucoside, being predominantly found in most soy products, including soy-based infant formulas, where GIN makes up > 65% of the isoflavone content [CITATION_6] . Infants consuming soy-based formulas have high circulating levels of GEN, the primary metabolite and aglycone form of GIN, ranging from 1.4 to 4.5 µM (381-1,224 ng/mL) [CITATION_7] ); a recent study reported the 25th, 50th, and 75th quartiles in serum as 405.3, 890.7, and 1455 .1 ng/mL (1.5, 3.3, and 5.4 µM, respectively) [CITATION_8] ), indicating that GIN is readily absorbed and hydrolyzed to the aglycone form, GEN.",
